lecture by distinguished humanist john brewer events at stanford lecture by distinguished humanist john brewer facebook twitter email print add to calendar volcanic tourism naples vesuvius and antiquity 1730 1850 why naples why vesuvius this talk examines how texts images models and performances about the bay of naples as a tourist destination combined culture and nature the volcano and antiquity individual reflection and aesthetic feeling to create a compelling narrative of modernity and its relation to antiquity one that was disseminated to a new public through much of europe and america by means of new forms of spectacular technology it examines an important moment in the transition from elite to mass tourism john brewer is the eli and edye broad professor of humanities and social sciences and professor of history and literature at caltech an expert in early modern british history and literature and early modern european history more generally he has written on the history of consumerism the history of post world war ii britain the history of collecting and the history of cultural patrimony among other subjects when thursday april 14 2011 4 00 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s where annenberg auditorium map audience faculty staff alumni friends general public students tags lecture reading visual arts sponsor department of art & art history history department contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free and open to the public permalink http events stanford edu events 274 27495 more info last modified april 12 2011
